                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/24142b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Dakar (<persName type="to">Flexer</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-09-02T22:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 2, 1942—10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>86. For your strictly confidential information the Embassy at Vichy reports that
                    it has been informed that Laval and Abetz<note n="46" xml:id="d355fn46">Otto
                        Abetz, German Ambassador in Paris.</note> held a conference at Nevers on
                    August 27 to discuss Dakar. It appears that previously the Germans had sought
                    permission to send a squadron of Stukas to Dakar, which threatened to provoke
                    the resignation of Boisson, who is thought to have been willing to accept the
                    Stukas but not German pilots. The Embassy has been informed that Boisson
                    recently forwarded his resignation to the Marshal<note n="47" xml:id="d355fn47"
                        >Marshal Henri Philippe Pétain, French Chief of State.</note> through Barrau
                    but that the Marshal would not accept it on the grounds that the proposed German
                    mission was only of a temporary character.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
